RF thermal-noise ranging/timing precision reference
===================================================

rf_ranging_reference.csv holds independently hand-computed RF tracking-loop
thermal-noise precision vectors (DLL code-tracking jitter -> ranging sigma; PLL
carrier-phase jitter -> timing floor) for a fully-specified S-band and Ka-band
deep-space case at the Earth-Moon range. It is used to cross-check Kshana's own
link-budget C/N0 (kshana::linkbudget::link_budget) and DLL code-tracking jitter
(kshana::navsignal::dll_code_jitter_chips) against an external analytic oracle
(see tests/validate_p5_rf_ranging_precision.rs). These files are not part of the
Kshana source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages — they exist
only for the test suite.

Oracle
------
Kaplan & Hegarty, "Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications", 3rd ed.
(Artech House, 2017), Ch. 8 "Fundamentals of Satellite Signal Tracking":

  * DLL coherent early-late code-tracking thermal jitter (eq. 8.90):
        sigma_code = sqrt( (B_L*d/(2*c)) * (1 + 2/((2-d)*T*c)) )   [chips, 1-sigma]
  * PLL carrier-phase thermal jitter (eq. 8.72, thermal term):
        sigma_phi = sqrt( B_L / c )                                [rad, 1-sigma]

with c the LINEAR C/N0. These are the textbook closed forms named in the P5
validation assessment ("Kaplan & Hegarty DLL/PLL tracking-jitter closed forms").
The C/N0 itself is the CCSDS-401 / DSN-810-005 one-way deep-space link equation
  C/N0 = EIRP - L_fs - L_other + G/T - k,  L_fs = 20*log10(4*pi*R*f/c),
recomputed by hand from constants.

Why this is a genuine independent check (non-circular)
------------------------------------------------------
The reference is computed in pure Python/NumPy from published textbook formulae
and physical constants — a DIFFERENT language and code path from the Rust engine
under test. The generator imports nothing from kshana. The Rust test then calls
the engine's OWN link_budget (to get C/N0 from EIRP/G/T/range) and OWN
dll_code_jitter_chips (to get the code jitter), and confronts them against these
hand values. If the engine's link equation or its DLL jitter formula were wrong,
the test would fail. The two implementations share only the underlying physics
(Friis loss, Kaplan & Hegarty tracking bounds), not code.

Scope / honesty
---------------
This validates the UNDERLYING physical quantities: the deep-space C/N0 and the
DLL/PLL thermal tracking jitter closed forms. It demonstrates that a forward
model built from those closed forms reproduces the Paper-5 Table-1 *ranging*
order of magnitude (S ~1 m, Ka ~0.1 m). The Paper-5 Table-1 *timing* headline
(~1 ns S / ~0.3 ns Ka) is NOT uniquely produced by either closed form — the
code-derived timing is ranging/c (~3 ns / ~0.43 ns) and the carrier-phase floor
is sub-picosecond — so the headline sigma is a chosen representative between the
code-ranging bound and the on-board clock stability and REMAINS Modelled. This
fixture validates the physics, it does not promote the Table-1 RF precision
number to Validated.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_rf_ranging_reference.py (run with Python 3 +
numpy 2.0.2). Deterministic: closed-form arithmetic, no randomness.

Format
------
rf_ranging_reference.csv: '#'-prefixed comment lines, then one ';'-separated row
per case:
  label;band;freq_hz;range_m;eirp_dbw;g_over_t_db;other_db;chip_rate_hz;
  loop_bw_hz;corr_spacing_chips;integ_time_s;fsl_db;cn0_dbhz;sigma_code_chips;
  sigma_range_m;sigma_code_time_ns;pll_phase_rad;pll_time_ps
